Of course you can use the complementary angle identities to diagonalize the expression, and here we are only dealing with integers. So the main challenge would be doing complex fraction multiplication, which is fine for a minute. Let's compute. First, denoting $x=\tan 9^\circ$, we have: \begin{align*}
\tan 9^\circ + \cot 9^\circ - \tan 27^\circ - \cot 27^\circ &= x + \frac{1}{x} + \left(\frac{3\tan 9^\circ - \tan^3 9^\circ}{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ}\right) - \left(\frac{\tan 27^\circ}{1 - \tan^2 27^\circ}\right)\\
&= \frac{x^2 + 1}{x} + \left(\frac{3x - x^3}{1 - 3x^2}\right) - \left(\frac{x}{1 - x^2}\right)\\
&= \frac{(x^2 + 1)(1 - x^2) + x(3x - x^3) - x(1 - 3x^2)}{x(1 - 3x^2)}\\
&= \frac{1 - x^4 + 2x^3}{x(1 - 3x^2)} = \boxed{\frac{(1 - x^2)^2}{x(1 - 3x^2)}}
\end{align*}
where $x=\tan 9^\circ$. <answer> $\frac{\left(1-\tan^2 9^\circ\right)^2}{\tan 9^\circ\left(1-3\tan^2 9^\circ\right)}$ </answer>

